2026-06-01T21:25:20.190+03:00 DEBUG 4376 --- [cat-handler-118] o.s.web.client.RestTemplate              : Accept=[text/plain, application/json, application/yaml, application/*+json, */*]
2026-06-01T21:25:20.191+03:00 DEBUG 4376 --- [cat-handler-118] o.s.web.client.RestTemplate              : Writing [{requests=[{model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Below is a RAG-ready POS user manual. Recommended document settings: `title`: POS User Manual - Sales, Shifts, Payments, and Receipts `module`: HELP `language`: en `document_type`: USER_MANUAL `source_type`: MANUAL `status`: ACTIVE ```markdown}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=POS User Manual}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Purpose The POS screen is used by cashiers and branch users to sell products, scan barcodes, manage the current cart, select customers, link repair tickets, take payments, print receipts, and work inside an open cashier shift. Use the POS when the user wants to: - Create a new sale or invoice. - Scan or search for products. - Add products to the cart. - Select a customer for the sale. - Link a repair ticket or IMEI to the sale. - Take payment by cash, card, wallet, or credit. - Print a receipt or invoice. - Review shift sales and cash movements. For analytics questions such as “How much did we sell today?” or “Who is the top cashier?”, use SQL/tools instead of this manual because those answers depend on live business data.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Accessing POS To open the POS: 1. Sign in to ValueInSoft. 2. Select the correct company and branch. 3. Open the main application workspace. 4. Choose the POS or Point of Sale screen. If the POS screen does not appear, the user may not have the required POS permissions. A manager or platform administrator should review the user role and capabilities.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Shift Requirement Most POS sale and payment actions require an open shift. If no shift is open: 1. Open the POS or POS Shift screen. 2. Enter the opening cash amount in the drawer. 3. Click Open Shift. 4. After the shift opens, cashiers can create sales and receipts. The opening amount should match the physical cash in the drawer at the start of the cashier shift.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Opening A Shift Steps to open a shift: 1. Go to POS or POS Shift. 2. Confirm that no shift is currently open for the branch. 3. Enter the opening safe balance or cash drawer amount. 4. Click Open Shift. 5. Confirm that the shift status is open. After the shift is open, the cashier can process sales, payments, cash movements, and receipts.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Product Search Products can be found in POS by: - Searching by product name. - Typing or scanning a barcode. - Selecting product tiles. - Filtering by category. - Filtering by subcategory. The product search box supports barcode scanners. Standard USB and Bluetooth barcode scanners usually work as keyboard input. If barcode autofocus is enabled for the branch, the POS search field stays ready for barcode scanning.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Barcode Scan To sell by barcode: 1. Click or focus the POS search field. 2. Scan the product barcode. 3. If the barcode matches a product, the product is added to the current sale. 4. If the barcode is not found, search by product name or confirm the barcode in inventory. If a scanned code is short, the system may treat it as a product search instead of a barcode search.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Serialized Products, IMEI, And Serial Numbers Some products may be tracked by serial number or IMEI. When selling serialized products: 1. Scan the serialized unit barcode, IMEI, or serial number. 2. Confirm the unit is available. 3. Add the unit to the cart. 4. Complete payment normally. If the unit is unavailable, already sold, reserved, or not available in this branch, the POS should not complete the sale for that unit. For serialized sale items, online availability may be required. If the POS says serialized items cannot be sold offline, reconnect and retry.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Adding Items To Cart To add a product to the current sale: 1. Search for the product by name or barcode. 2. Click Add or select the product tile. 3. Confirm the item appears in Current Sale. 4. Adjust quantity if needed. 5. Repeat for all products. The cart shows selected products, quantities, prices, discounts, and totals.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Current Sale Cart The Current Sale cart is the working invoice before payment. In the cart, the cashier can: - Review selected products. - Change quantities. - Remove incorrect items. - View subtotal and total. - Apply available discounts if permitted. - Select or switch the customer. - Continue to payment. If the cart is empty, no sale can be completed.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Selecting A Customer A sale can be assigned to a customer. To assign a customer: 1. Open the customer selector in the cart. 2. Search for the customer. 3. Select the correct customer. 4. Continue the sale. If no customer is selected, the sale may use a guest/default customer. Use a real customer when: - The customer will pay later on credit. - The sale should affect customer balance. - The customer needs receipt history. - The customer is linked to a repair ticket.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Guest Customer Guest Customer is used when the buyer does not need a saved customer profile. Use Guest Customer for simple cash/card/wallet walk-in sales. Do not use Guest Customer when the transaction must be tracked against a specific customer balance, repair record, or credit payment.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Linking Repair Ticket Or IMEI The POS can link a repair ticket or IMEI to the current sale. To link a repair ticket: 1. Find the Link Ticket / IMEI field. 2. Enter the repair ticket ID or customer IMEI. 3. Click Load Ticket. 4. The POS loads the repair service fee and any used parts. 5. The ticket customer is linked to the sale when available. 6. Complete payment from the cart. If the ticket is already paid, it cannot be paid again from POS. If the ticket is not found, check the ticket number, IMEI, or repair module record.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Repair Ticket Payment When a repair ticket is loaded into POS: - Repair service fees may be added as a sale item. - Used spare parts may be added as sale items. - The customer from the ticket may be selected automatically. - The sale may be linked back to the repair ticket. Complete payment normally after reviewing the items and total.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Discounts Discounts may appear from: - Manual discount rules. - POS offers. - Product-specific promotions. - Manager-approved adjustments. Before completing payment, verify: - The discount amount is correct. - The total after discount is correct. - The customer understands the final amount. If a discount is not available, the user may not have permission or the offer may be inactive, expired, or not applicable to the selected products.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Payment Methods Supported payment methods may include: - Cash. - Card. - Wallet or Instapay. - Credit or unpaid customer balance. Available payment methods depend on company settings, finance configuration, and user permissions.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Completing A Sale Steps to complete a sale: 1. Add products to Current Sale. 2. Select a customer if needed. 3. Review quantities, prices, discount, and grand total. 4. Click Proceed or Pay. 5. Choose payment method. 6. Enter the received amount if required. 7. Submit payment. 8. Print or save the receipt. After payment is submitted, the order is saved and inventory is updated.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Cash Payment For cash payment: 1. Select Cash. 2. Enter the amount received from the customer. 3. Confirm the change due if shown. 4. Submit payment. 5. Put the received cash into the drawer. 6. Give the customer the printed receipt. The cash payment affects expected cash in the current shift.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Card Or Wallet Payment For card or wallet payment: 1. Select Card, Wallet, or Instapay as available. 2. Confirm payment succeeded on the external terminal or wallet app. 3. Enter or confirm the amount. 4. Submit payment in POS. 5. Give the customer the receipt. Do not submit the POS payment before confirming the external payment succeeded.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Credit Sale Or Customer Balance Use credit only when the customer is known and allowed to carry a balance. Before credit payment: 1. Select the correct customer. 2. Confirm the customer account. 3. Choose the credit or unpaid balance payment method. 4. Submit the sale. Credit sales should not be assigned to Guest Customer.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Receipt Printing After payment, POS can print a receipt or invoice. Supported formats may include: - Thermal receipt. - A5 invoice. - A4 invoice. Receipts may include: - Company details. - Branch details. - Order number. - Date and time. - Cashier. - Customer. - Product lines. - Serialized identifiers or IMEI when applicable. - Discount. - Tax if configured. - Total and payment status. - Barcode or receipt reference. If printing fails, confirm printer settings, browser permissions, and printer connection.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Returns And Exchange Note Receipts may include return policy text. The customer should keep the original receipt for returns, exchanges, pickup, or warranty review. Return policy depends on company settings and store policy.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Cash Movements During Shift Managers or authorized cashiers may record cash movements during an open shift. Common cash movement types: - Cash In or Paid In. - Cash Out or Paid Out. - Safe Drop. Use cash movements when cash enters or leaves the drawer outside normal sales.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Safe Drop A Safe Drop records money removed from the cash drawer and moved to a safe or manager custody. Use Safe Drop when: - Drawer cash is too high. - Store policy requires periodic cash removal. - A manager collects cash before shift close. A Safe Drop should include the amount and reason. It affects drawer reconciliation.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Paid In Paid In records extra cash added to the drawer during a shift. Examples: - Additional float added by a manager. - Cash correction approved by management. Paid In increases expected cash.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Paid Out Paid Out records cash removed from the drawer for approved reasons. Examples: - Small cash expense. - Refund cash movement. - Manager-approved cash withdrawal. Paid Out decreases expected cash.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Shift Sales Review The POS Shift screen can show shift activity such as: - Gross sales. - Net sales. - Discounts. - Orders. - Customer receipts. - Cash movements. - Expected cash. - Drawer count. - Variance. Use this screen before closing the shift to confirm the drawer and sales activity.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Closing A Shift Steps to close a shift: 1. Open the POS Shift screen. 2. Review sales, receipts, discounts, and cash movements. 3. Count physical cash in the drawer. 4. Enter the drawer closing amount. 5. Review expected cash and variance. 6. Confirm Close Shift. If there is a variance, verify sales, cash payments, paid in, paid out, and safe drops before confirming.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Force Closing A Shift Force close is a manager action used when a normal close cannot be completed. Use force close only when: - A cashier forgot to close a shift. - A system or operational issue blocked normal close. - Management approves the reason. Always enter a clear reason when force closing.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Finance Posting POS sales, payments, discounts, taxes, cash drawer movements, and closing entries may create finance posting requests. If finance posting fails: - The sale may still be saved. - The posting request may show failed status. - Finance or admin users should review posting requests. - Common causes include missing account mappings, closed fiscal periods, or invalid finance setup. Cashiers should not retry finance posting unless they have permission and understand the error.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Inventory Impact Completing a POS sale reduces inventory for sold products. For serialized products, the specific unit may be marked sold or unavailable after sale. If stock does not update: - Confirm the sale was completed successfully. - Check whether the order was saved. - Check inventory transactions. - Confirm the product belongs to the correct branch.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Offline POS Notes Some POS features may support offline operation, but not all actions are safe offline. Serialized items may require online validation. If serialized sale items are present and the system blocks offline payment, reconnect before completing the sale. When offline sync is used, wait for synchronization before relying on final reports or finance posting status.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Common Problems And Fixes Problem: Product not found by barcode. Fix: Search by product name, confirm the barcode in inventory, or update the product barcode. Problem: Product appears unavailable. Fix: Check branch stock, serialized unit status, and whether the item is reserved or already sold. Problem: Cannot complete sale. Fix: Confirm there is an open shift, cart has items, payment method is selected, and user has permission. Problem: Cannot use credit payment. Fix: Select a real customer instead of Guest Customer and confirm customer credit is allowed. Problem: Repair ticket not found. Fix: Check the ticket ID, IMEI, and repair module record. Problem: Ticket already paid. Fix: Do not create another POS payment for the same ticket. Review ticket history. Problem: Receipt does not print. Fix: Check printer connection, printer name/profile, paper size, browser print permissions, and retry print. Problem: Shift cash does not balance. Fix: Review cash sales, customer receipts, paid in, paid out, safe drops, refunds, and physical cash count. Problem: Finance posting failed. Fix: Ask finance/admin to review posting requests and account mappings.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Best Practices For Cashiers - Open the shift before selling. - Confirm the branch before starting work. - Scan barcodes when possible to reduce errors. - Review cart totals before payment. - Select the customer when the sale affects customer balance. - Do not use Guest Customer for credit sales. - Confirm external card or wallet payment before submitting POS payment. - Print or provide a receipt after each sale. - Record cash movements immediately. - Count cash carefully before closing the shift.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=Best Practices For Managers - Review open shifts daily. - Investigate cash variances before closing. - Use safe drops for large cash drawers. - Review failed finance postings. - Confirm POS finance mappings are active. - Keep product barcodes and serialized units accurate. - Train cashiers to select customers correctly. - Periodically compare POS reports with cash drawer and finance reports.}]}}, {model=models/text-embedding-004, content={parts=[{text=When To Use RAG Versus Live Data Tools Use this manual for questions about how to use POS features, such as: - How do I open a shift? - How do I scan a product? - How do I link a repair ticket? - How do I close a shift? - What is a safe drop? - Why should I select a customer? Use SQL/tools for live data questions, such as: - What were today’s sales? - Which cashier sold the most? - Which products are low stock? - What is the current open shift? - Which finance postings failed? - How much cash should be in the drawer? ```}]}}]}] as "application/json"
